  "text": "The experimental setup is depicted in Fig. 5a . At the transmitter, external cavity lasers (ECL) are used to generate 50GHz spaced wavelength channels centered on 1547.72 nm. The channels are modulated with a 10 GBaud QPSK pseudo random bit sequence (PRBS) of length 2 [CITATION_1] using an IQ modulator driven by two synchronized digital analog converters (DACs). This sequence is generated using a novel round-robin (RR) encoder which is based on a space-time code [CITATION_2] . The round-robin coding averages the overall system performance by allocating time slots of data channels over all the transmitted spatial channels. In this setup data channel 0 ≤ m ≤ 19 is allocated to transmission channel 0 ≤ n ≤ 19 at time slot 0 ≤ k ≤ ∞ as n = mod 20 (m + k), where mod 20 is the modulus after division by 20 function. Figure 5b provides a graphical representation of the round robin coding scheme. It is important to note that the theoretical implication is small, however the hardware considerations for potential implementation are challenging due to timing implications. Critical timing alignment is required at the transmitter and receiver side for decoding the channels in DSP.",
